{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488396","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488396"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:40:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:40:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"430"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"430","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/430"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.29,0.02,0.09,0.6,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"430"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105773"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"430","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/430"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"430"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88241"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"2411"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2801"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2859"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33213"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38811"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105773","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105773"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a painless swelling in his upper abdomen. This has been present for two years and is most noticeable when he stands or strains. He has a medical history of gastro-oesophageal reflux disease and type 2 diabetes. His regular medications include esomeprazole and metformin. He has had a left knee arthroplasty but no abdominal surgical procedures. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His BMI is 34 kg/m\u00b2. The abdominal swelling is most evident when he lies down (Image 1) and is asked to lift his legs off the bed (Image 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Epigastric hernia","Umbilical hernia","Paraumbilical hernia","Rectus divarication","Incisional hernia"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a midline abdominal bulge that becomes more prominent with abdominal muscle engagement (lifting legs while supine). The key features supporting the diagnosis are the diffuse nature of the bulge along the midline, its enhancement with muscle contraction, and the absence of prior abdominal surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERectus divarication\u003C/strong\u003E (also called diastasis recti) is a separation of the rectus abdominis muscles along the linea alba. This is not a true hernia as there is no fascial defect or hernia sac - rather, the rectus muscles have become weakened and separated, allowing abdominal contents to protrude forward when intra-abdominal pressure increases. Risk factors include obesity, multiple pregnancies, and age-related muscle weakness. Management primarily involves weight loss and core-strengthening exercises rather than surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpigastric hernia\u003C/strong\u003E presents as a discrete, often small (2-3 cm) defect in the linea alba between the xiphoid process and umbilicus. Unlike the diffuse bulge seen in this patient, epigastric hernias typically have a well-defined edge and often contain only preperitoneal fat. They are frequently irreducible due to the small size of the fascial defect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUmbilical hernia\u003C/strong\u003E occurs through the umbilical ring and presents as a protrusion at the umbilicus itself. The images show a bulge extending well above the umbilicus, making this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParaumbilical hernia\u003C/strong\u003E occurs through a defect in the linea alba adjacent to the umbilicus. While these can be larger than umbilical hernias, they remain centered around the umbilical region and do not typically extend up to the xiphoid process as seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncisional hernia\u003C/strong\u003E occurs at the site of previous surgical incisions due to fascial weakness. Since this patient has no history of abdominal surgery, an incisional hernia can be excluded.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Rectus divarication (diastasis recti) is a separation of the rectus abdominis muscles that appears as a midline bulge when abdominal muscles are engaged.","Rectus divarication is distinguished from hernias by the absence of a true fascial defect and hernia sac.","Management of rectus divarication primarily involves weight loss and core strengthening exercises rather than surgical repair."],"references":["Mommers EHH, Ponten JEH, Omar AKA, de Vries Reilingh TS, Bouvy ND, Nienhuijs SW. The general surgeon\u2019s perspective of rectus diastasis. A systematic review of treatment options. Surg Endosc. 2017; 31(12): 4934-4949. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28597282/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88241"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"430"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19689"},{"type":"media","id":"19690"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19689","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19689"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/dac6d4df-64e3-4f3e-91fa-faa746083814.jpg","thumbUrl